\begin_layout Standard
The most popular and well-known meta-analysis method is the random effects
 model with normal likelihoods (Borenstein).
 Written in hierarchical notation, it equals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\theta & \sim & N(\theta_{0},\tau),\\
x_{i}\mid\theta,\sigma & \sim & N(\theta,\sqrt{\tau^{2}+\sigma_{i}^{2}}).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the standard deviation of the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th study.
 Following the convention in meta-analysis, we assume these parameters to
 be known.
 The mean parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is the population effect size, and 
\begin_inset Formula $N(\theta_{0},\tau)$
\end_inset

 is the effect size distribution.
 The parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is the heterogeneity parameter.
 The purpose of the effect size distribution is to model the fact that most
 effect size estimates plugged into a meta-analysis do not appear to come
 from exactly the same phenomenon.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the simplest of these models, only significant results are observed.
 In this case,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f(x;\theta_{0},\sigma_{i})=\Phi\left(\frac{\theta_{0}-c_{\alpha}}{\sqrt{\sigma_{i}+\tau}}\right)^{-1}\phi(x;\theta_{0},\sqrt{\sigma_{i}^{2}+\tau^{2}}),\label{eq:selection for significance model}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\alpha}=\Phi^{-1}(1-\alpha)$
\end_inset

 for some significance level 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

