\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "exa:t-test"

\end_inset

 Consider the usual 
\emph on
t
\emph default
-confidence interval with 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 observations.
 Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 contains all measures 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\mu,\sigma}^{n}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\mu,\sigma}$
\end_inset

 is the probability measure of a normal with mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and standard deviation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(\mu)=\{P_{\mu,\sigma}^{n}\mid\sigma>0\}$
\end_inset

 contain all normal probability measures with mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and some positive standard deviation.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(\mu),\mu\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 defined a partition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

.
 A 
\emph on
t
\emph default
-confidence interval is a confidence set of size 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 according to definition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "def:confidence set"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we must find out how to measure the size of confidence sets.
 Let a size function be any positive function 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \cdot\right\Vert :\Pi\to[0,\infty)$
\end_inset

.
 In the 
\emph on
t
\emph default
-confidence interval example above, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \cdot\right\Vert $
\end_inset

 can be taken to be the absolute value of the unique 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 associated with each 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The diameter of a confidence set is the random variable
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D(\omega)=\sup_{\pi\in\Pi}\{\left\Vert \pi\right\Vert \mid\omega\notin R(\pi)\}\label{eq:diameter}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

That is, the diameter tells you the size of the largest accepted 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

.
 We will assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is Borel measurable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A confidence set has infinite diameter with 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

-positive probability if 
\begin_inset Formula $P(D=\infty)$
\end_inset

.
 It has infinite diameter with positive probability if 
\begin_inset Formula $P(D=\infty)>0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $P\in\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This theorem is a slight generalization of the Gleser–Hwang theorem.
 
